pageType: content
background:
  type: solid
  color: "$background"
elements:
  - elementId: page-title
    elementType: text
    bounds: [80, 30, 1120, 35]
    content:
      style: "$actionTitle"
      align: [left, middle]
      wrap: false
      text: |
        <p><strong>Research Gap: Quadratic Complexity Limits Scalability Beyond 4K Tokens</strong></p>

  - elementId: title-divider
    elementType: shape
    bounds: [80, 72, 80, 2]
    shapeName: rect
    fill:
      type: solid
      color: "$primary"

  - elementId: problem-statement
    elementType: text
    bounds: [80, 95, 560, 200]
    content:
      style: "$body"
      align: [left, top]
      text: |
        <p><strong>Problem Statement</strong></p>
        <p style="margin-top:6px">Standard self-attention computes pairwise token interactions with \(O(n^2)\) time and memory complexity, creating a fundamental bottleneck for long-document processing where \(n > 10,000\).</p>
        <p style="margin-top:6px">Existing sparse approximations sacrifice either local coherence (global patterns) or long-range dependencies (local patterns), failing to achieve both simultaneously.</p>

  - elementId: motivation-chart
    elementType: chart
    bounds: [680, 95, 520, 250]
    type: bar
    data:
      - {method: "Full Attn", complexity: 100, accuracy: 100}
      - {method: "Sparse A", complexity: 25, accuracy: 72}
      - {method: "Sparse B", complexity: 30, accuracy: 78}
      - {method: "Linear A", complexity: 8, accuracy: 65}
      - {method: "Linear B", complexity: 10, accuracy: 70}
    x: method
    y: [complexity, accuracy]
    names: ["Relative Complexity", "Relative Accuracy (%)"]
    colors: ["#94A3B8", "$primary"]
    options:
      fontFamily: "Arial, Microsoft YaHei"
    legend:
      show: true
      position: top
      fontSize: 12
    yAxis:
      title: "Relative Scale"
      gridLine:
        color: "#F1F5F9"
        style: solid
        width: 1
      label:
        fontSize: 12
        color: "$textLight"
    xAxis:
      label:
        fontSize: 12
        color: "$textLight"

  - elementId: research-questions
    elementType: text
    bounds: [80, 310, 1120, 180]
    content:
      style: "$body"
      align: [left, top]
      text: |
        <p><strong>Research Questions</strong></p>
        <p style="margin-top:6px"><strong>RQ1:</strong> Can we design an attention mechanism that achieves sub-quadratic complexity without sacrificing the expressiveness required for long-document understanding tasks?</p>
        <p style="margin-top:6px"><strong>RQ2:</strong> What is the theoretical relationship between sparsity pattern and representational capacity for hierarchical document structures?</p>
        <p style="margin-top:6px"><strong>RQ3:</strong> Does the proposed method generalize across diverse long-document benchmarks (summarization, QA, retrieval)?</p>

  - elementId: methodology-overview
    elementType: text
    bounds: [80, 505, 1120, 90]
    content:
      style: "$body"
      align: [left, top]
      text: |
        <p><strong>Methodological Approach</strong></p>
        <p style="margin-top:4px">We decompose attention into three granularities: (1) <strong>sentence-level</strong> local windows, (2) <strong>paragraph-level</strong> compressed representations, and (3) <strong>document-level</strong> global tokens. This hierarchical decomposition reduces complexity to \(O(n \log n)\) while preserving both local and global dependencies.</p>

  - elementId: page-num
    elementType: text
    bounds: [1180, 680, 60, 20]
    content:
      style: "$pageNumber"
      align: [right, middle]
      wrap: false
      text: |
        <p>04</p>
